<div class="content">
  <h2>Enameled vs Traditional Cast Iron</h2>
  <p>Traditional bare cast iron requires seasoning to maintain a non-stick surface and prevent rust. It's incredibly durable and can withstand extreme temperatures, making it ideal for searing and campfire cooking. Enameled cast iron features a glass-particulate coating that eliminates the need for seasoning and won't react with acidic foods like tomatoes, but it can chip if dropped or subjected to rapid temperature changes.</p>

  <h2>Seasoning Guide</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Wash the skillet thoroughly with soap and water.</li>
    <li>Dry completely over low heat on the stovetop.</li>
    <li>Apply a very thin, even layer of high-smoke-point oil (like flaxseed or canola) over the entire surface, inside and out.</li>
    <li>Wipe away excess oil until the pan looks almost dry.</li>
    <li>Bake upside down in a 400°F-500°F oven for 1 hour. Place foil on the bottom rack to catch any drips.</li>
    <li>Let it cool in the oven. Repeat 2-3 times for a better non-stick surface.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Cleaning Tips</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Wash by hand while the skillet is still warm (not hot) using hot water.</li>
    <li>Use a specialized chainmail scrubber, a stiff brush, or a sponge. Avoid harsh steel wool on seasoned cast iron.</li>
    <li>A few drops of mild dish soap are perfectly fine and won't strip the seasoning.</li>
    <li>For stuck-on food, simmer a little water in the pan for 3-5 minutes, then scrape with a spatula after it cools.</li>
    <li>Dry immediately and thoroughly with a towel or by heating it on the stove for a few minutes.</li>
    <li>Lightly rub with cooking oil while still warm to protect the seasoning.</li>
  </ul>

