  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between enameled and traditional cast iron?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Traditional bare cast iron requires seasoning and is nearly indestructible. Enameled cast iron has a glass-like coating that prevents rusting and doesn't require seasoning, but the enamel can chip if mistreated.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How do I season a new cast iron skillet?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Wash the skillet, dry it completely, apply a very thin layer of high-smoke-point oil (like flaxseed, grapeseed, or canola), and bake it upside down in a 400°F-500°F oven for one hour. Let it cool in the oven.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Can I use soap to clean my cast iron?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Yes, contrary to popular belief, a few drops of mild dish soap will not ruin your seasoning. Modern dish soaps don't contain lye, which is what used to strip seasoning in the past.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Why is my cast iron skillet sticky?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">A sticky skillet usually means too much oil was used during the seasoning process, or the temperature wasn't high enough to fully polymerize the oil. Bake the skillet again at a higher temperature to fix this.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Is a heavier cast iron skillet better?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Not necessarily. Heavier skillets retain heat better and heat more evenly, but they can be difficult to maneuver. Lighter skillets are easier to handle but may have hot spots.</div>
    </div>
